is when someone rejects me when all they know about me is that I’m trans See if you talk with the people I live with and the people I work with they can tell you lots of things about me But if you talk to my relatives they can’t tell you anything because they don’t know anything about me The father is the most clueless one of all He can’t tell you when my birthday is (whether biological or by “name-day”) he can’t tell you who my best friend is or what my favorite color is He can’t tell you what I want to do for a living He can’t even tell you how to spell my legal middle name (even though he’s the one who named me) He can’t tell you who my favorite teachers are or who my heroes are or what my favorite classes were when I was in school He can’t tell you what my hobbies are or where is my favorite place to be He can’t tell you what my sexuality is what my favorite or least favorite (or most hated) foods are or who my favorite writers and artists are He can’t tell you anything about my favorite books movies bands songs games--he can’t tell you what my most precious belongings were before he threw me and them away He can’t tell you about the things I dream about at night that make call family even though they’ve never loved me or even tried to hug me He can’t tell you about how his son and daughter would try to kill me everyday and night for the first nine and a half years of my life or that they’d do that just because they were bored He can’t tell you how much I’ve missed my mom a monster who taught her firstborns how to kill Yet I still wish she was around He can’t tell you why I accept and respect everyone I meet even before talking to them; like fear and hate have ever cured the blind He can’t tell you how I strive to be perfect like I’m better than a robot as an experiment to see if it’ll make him like me or maybe even respect me as though I’m actually alive not living a lie He can’t tell you I’m actually his son and that he just made a mistake for the first nineteen years of my life The reason (which is actually an excuse) is because I was the mistake from the very start The reason--the real reason--is because he’s too much a disgrace to pick himself up when you need to: (Keekee) We’re indebted to psychiatrists Thomas Holmes and Richard Rahe for the insightful research that led to the Holmes-Rahe Stress Scale The now-famous scale details the 43 life events that are most liable to create feelings of grief and in turn cause illness and other health-related problems Although we use the word grief rather than stress we are in total accord with the list of grief-producing events Our only problem with the list is that it is comparative and as such ranks losses in a hierarchy on a point system Since we believe all loss is experienced at 100%—even though not all losses are equal—we choose to present the list in the same order as Holmes-Rahe created it; with the only difference being that we omit the listing of point totals for each loss We’d like to point out that not all of the life experiences on the list would logically be viewed as stressors or grief or loss events Note that near the top of the list is “marriage ” While we all know that the wedding day can be stressful and that marriage is not without problems we also know it’s often referred to as one of the greatest days of our lives Additionally the list includes “change in financial state ” which is not limited to losing money but includes the impact of a sudden windfall like winning the lottery Our definition of Grief: “Grief is the conflicting feelings caused by the end of or change in a familiar pattern of behavior ” In addition to the life-events listed we add a few more under the heading of “intangible ” for example: Loss of Trust Loss of Approval Loss of
